1
00:00:00,031 --> 00:00:13,686
Namo tassa bhagavato arhato samma-sambuddhasam Homage to the Buddha, the Blessed Noble, and fully self-enlightened.

2
00:00:15,768 --> 00:00:26,460
So, just to thank Vikram Daya for this opportunity to come and give a talk, and of course to thank them for me saying this,

3
00:00:26,795 --> 00:00:34,944
for the dedication that they put in to establish a little meditation center right here in the middle of the top nest.

4
00:00:34,963 --> 00:00:38,468
Sadhu!

5
00:00:38,487 --> 00:00:41,210
Sadhu!

6
00:00:42,932 --> 00:00:43,173
Sadhu!

7
00:00:43,192 --> 00:00:52,902
So I thought it might be an opportunity really just to go over some basic teachings as a reminder.

8
00:00:56,393 --> 00:01:02,738
just looking at the Buddha's life itself, just recognizing that he is an exemplar.

9
00:01:02,759 --> 00:01:07,463
The life that he lived is really what we ourselves have to go through.

10
00:01:09,125 --> 00:01:10,186
He's a teacher, of course.

11
00:01:11,268 --> 00:01:15,912
And in the sense that it's a path that everybody has to take, one way or the other.

12
00:01:16,031 --> 00:01:16,992
And I mean everybody.

13
00:01:17,694 --> 00:01:19,194
He's an archetype.

14
00:01:19,215 --> 00:01:20,777
So it's a path of renunciation.

15
00:01:21,537 --> 00:01:23,920
Not to be confused with mortifications.

16
00:01:24,591 --> 00:01:29,376
So renunciation, remember, is just the letting go of a wrong relationship we have with the world.

17
00:01:31,278 --> 00:01:36,284
In those times there were, very similar to ours, two basic philosophies.

18
00:01:36,343 --> 00:01:42,010
One was that it was just materialism, what we would call materialism, scientific materialism.

19
00:01:43,090 --> 00:01:47,034
One life and that's it, so you may as well enjoy yourself.

20
00:01:47,055 --> 00:01:53,501
And he probably tried that as a youth, got fed up with it, became empty, and that was one of the reasons that he

21
00:01:53,852 --> 00:01:54,674
He began to leave.

22
00:01:55,394 --> 00:02:01,381
One of our deepest fears is that we want to enjoy life.

23
00:02:01,400 --> 00:02:08,269
And the other one was that there was some sort of soul or spirit within us which was held down by karma.

24
00:02:08,709 --> 00:02:12,712
And in the Jain tradition, this is quite material.

25
00:02:12,733 --> 00:02:15,896
It's your actual physical body, you might say.

26
00:02:15,917 --> 00:02:20,822
And the whole idea was to practice mortification exercises which were then

27
00:02:21,206 --> 00:02:23,788
allow the soul to leave the body.

28
00:02:24,189 --> 00:02:29,114
So the James Saint, the one who is a hero, is one who starts himself to death.

29
00:02:32,137 --> 00:02:33,858
The Buddha himself tried these, of course.

30
00:02:34,218 --> 00:02:43,986
He tried to get into these beautiful mental states, which was part of the idea of some sort of eternality, and found them wanting.

31
00:02:44,026 --> 00:02:49,391
He kept waking up and finding himself to be still, the depressed Gautama.

32
00:02:49,944 --> 00:02:51,306
anxious and depressed.

33
00:02:52,388 --> 00:03:01,581
And remember that he had this, we could say that he was going through what we would call an existential crisis, coming to terms with sickness, aging and death.

34
00:03:04,445 --> 00:03:08,991
And then he tried the self-mortification business and found that it was just more suffering.

35
00:03:09,012 --> 00:03:10,033
So he abandoned that.

36
00:03:10,854 --> 00:03:18,264
So we can imagine him on the road, having left his companions, feeling quite despairing.

37
00:03:18,284 --> 00:03:19,546
And along comes a woman

38
00:03:19,949 --> 00:03:37,868
for some reason we know her name, Sujata, fortunate birth, who sees him, and although she's carrying special sweetmeats, little rice cakes, though I prefer to always think of it as rice pudding, and sees this poor wretch and offers her offerings to him.

39
00:03:38,149 --> 00:03:40,371
In the scriptures, of course, it says he was glowing like a god.

40
00:03:41,512 --> 00:03:42,233
This is ridiculous.

41
00:03:43,014 --> 00:03:46,598
So he was there looking quite wretched, and he took this rice pudding,

42
00:03:47,371 --> 00:03:53,360
And, as you know, the effect of rice pudding is, of course, incalculable.

43
00:03:56,424 --> 00:04:08,802
At that point he has a memory from childhood, and this is really why we call him self-enlightened, because in this memory from childhood he remembers watching his father doing a ploughing ceremony.

44
00:04:08,823 --> 00:04:15,032
And he recognizes that he's in the same state of absorption that he would have been in these

45
00:04:15,805 --> 00:04:17,927
practices of absorption of the Jhanic state.

46
00:04:18,867 --> 00:04:21,951
But there's something extra to it, which is a sense of curiosity.

47
00:04:22,911 --> 00:04:25,634
So he's driven by interest to know what his father is doing.

48
00:04:27,137 --> 00:04:30,800
At that point, his whole search, his whole labor turns upon itself.

49
00:04:31,581 --> 00:04:36,505
So instead of trying to seek happiness, he now tries to understand how he's creating suffering.

50
00:04:38,127 --> 00:04:42,031
And with that new inspiration, he sits under the Bodhi tree,

51
00:04:42,517 --> 00:04:46,884
And there's a great determination, either he's going to crack this problem or die.

52
00:04:48,045 --> 00:04:51,589
Well, lucky for him, and very fortunate for us, he cracks it.

53
00:04:51,750 --> 00:04:53,593
Six hours, that's what he said it took.

54
00:04:54,834 --> 00:05:00,603
And what he realized, what he has experienced is something which he can't explain.

55
00:05:00,622 --> 00:05:05,428
He calls it ineffable, beyond rationality.

56
00:05:05,449 --> 00:05:09,555
He has all these lovely epithets, and he points to it often, or mostly,

57
00:05:09,855 --> 00:05:10,697
in the negative.

58
00:05:10,757 --> 00:05:13,178
It's not born, doesn't die, not conditioned.

59
00:05:14,880 --> 00:05:18,144
He then gives it a name, Nirvana.

60
00:05:18,204 --> 00:05:26,531
But in the Theravada tradition it's the negative side which is mostly accentuated.

61
00:05:26,711 --> 00:05:33,817
That Nirvana is nothing that can be described, it's an emptiness and all that sort of stuff.

62
00:05:33,838 --> 00:05:38,461
In the Mahayana they're much more positive about it and there are two

63
00:05:38,762 --> 00:05:45,149
two occasions in the scriptures which, in a sense, give us the more Mahayana point of view.

64
00:05:46,791 --> 00:05:55,562
So we have a collection of scriptures called the Udana Suttas which are the inspirational phrases that the Buddha came out with.

65
00:05:56,283 --> 00:06:05,973
So somebody collected them all into this special collection and it doesn't include these two instances.

66
00:06:05,994 --> 00:06:08,297
So it gives you the slant of a particular school

67
00:06:09,002 --> 00:06:18,557
These two instances say quite clearly that there is a consciousness which is not touched by any of the senses, which includes the mind.

68
00:06:19,459 --> 00:06:21,702
No emotions, no thoughts, etc.

69
00:06:23,266 --> 00:06:24,466
Without boundary.

70
00:06:25,949 --> 00:06:28,112
Only phenomena can create boundary.

71
00:06:28,132 --> 00:06:30,317
And in all directions full of light.

72
00:06:30,336 --> 00:06:33,321
Just this is the end of suffering.

73
00:06:33,341 --> 00:06:36,867
So we have to find within us this Buddha,

74
00:06:39,833 --> 00:06:54,264
This Buddha that's within us, this satipanya, this intuitive awareness, is completely confused with the body and mind, with the psychophysical organism.

75
00:06:55,805 --> 00:06:59,149
And because of that confusion, it seeks happiness in this form.

76
00:07:00,690 --> 00:07:03,833
Seeking happiness in this form leads ultimately to frustration.

77
00:07:05,495 --> 00:07:09,637
And what it does is it makes us collect things to be acquisitive

78
00:07:10,259 --> 00:07:14,103
thinking that the more we have, the more happy, the more secure we'll be.

79
00:07:14,903 --> 00:07:17,947
So more money, more friends, and more power.

80
00:07:19,689 --> 00:07:28,139
And we find that this isn't ever completely satisfactory, because I'm never completely safe, so I always have to have a little more money.

81
00:07:28,619 --> 00:07:32,262
I'm never entirely loved, so I need a couple more friends.

82
00:07:33,004 --> 00:07:36,687
And I'm never quite in control, so I need a little more power.

83
00:07:37,326 --> 00:07:52,343
And so it grows, and in those actions we form unskillful deeds, which create within us our suffering, our conditioning, our unskillful conditioning.

84
00:07:52,363 --> 00:08:02,254
Then one day we wake up and we discover vipassana, or any meditation, and the process now is in reverse.

85
00:08:02,274 --> 00:08:06,540
The process is to observe within us how we've created this world,

86
00:08:07,398 --> 00:08:17,769
When we say we've created this world, the room we're sitting in now has, we can presume, some sort of objective of existence.

87
00:08:18,170 --> 00:08:20,052
In other words, it can be here when we all leave.

88
00:08:20,973 --> 00:08:25,959
But the room that we're actually experiencing is entirely created by us.

89
00:08:27,600 --> 00:08:30,184
It depends upon our sight, our hearing, our body.

90
00:08:32,145 --> 00:08:36,291
And we live within this cocoon, this bubble of consciousness.

91
00:08:37,822 --> 00:08:50,116
And this bubble of consciousness gives us the impression that we are objective about the world, especially in the West where we confuse ourselves into thinking that we can see the world objectively.

92
00:08:50,937 --> 00:08:58,086
It's of course thought about our science and our technology, but it's left us with a delusion.

93
00:08:58,105 --> 00:09:06,615
And what the meditation tells us is that the world we're actually living in is being created entirely by us from very minimal

94
00:09:07,220 --> 00:09:08,881
stimuli from the outside.

95
00:09:10,623 --> 00:09:12,785
At the eardrum, all there is is pressure.

96
00:09:14,287 --> 00:09:18,030
At the skin level, there's only little chemical, electrical changes.

97
00:09:18,871 --> 00:09:25,958
The eyes collect a very small amount of photons, and the rest of it is completely manufactured within us.

98
00:09:27,379 --> 00:09:35,808
And so, when we consider that the world that I am actually living in is the one that I am creating, then the question must arise,

99
00:09:36,211 --> 00:09:37,793
Why are they such a pig's ear?

100
00:09:38,894 --> 00:09:42,938
And that's basically our investigation.

101
00:09:44,360 --> 00:09:57,316
In taking a stance within us, which we call the observer, the feeler, we have disengaged with the psychophysical organism.

102
00:09:57,336 --> 00:09:58,817
What do we mean by self?

103
00:09:58,837 --> 00:10:00,340
We mean identity.

104
00:10:00,899 --> 00:10:02,302
What does identity mean?

105
00:10:02,322 --> 00:10:05,525
It means basically that for that moment, that's what you are.

106
00:10:06,046 --> 00:10:08,831
There are single moments where this comes across to us.

107
00:10:08,850 --> 00:10:17,966
For instance, when you trap your finger in the door, for that one lovely, delightful moment, you and the pain are one and the same.

108
00:10:17,985 --> 00:10:19,548
That's identity.

109
00:10:19,568 --> 00:10:27,501
When you get lost in a daydream and you're lost in the emotional inner DVD, that's what you are.

110
00:10:27,763 --> 00:10:29,184
That's what we mean by identity.

111
00:10:29,840 --> 00:10:36,106
As soon as you jump out of it, you've lost that identity and formed another identity of the one who knows.

112
00:10:38,288 --> 00:10:50,082
The whole process of our liberation from that delusion is the process of pulling ourselves out of what we thought was me, what we thought was us.

113
00:10:51,864 --> 00:10:53,866
Consider the child who's born.

114
00:10:54,407 --> 00:10:58,631
We're told there was a lot of research done, even going back to Freud,

115
00:10:59,118 --> 00:11:10,089
there was a psychologist called Margaret Mahler, I think that was her name, who did extensive study on how a child finally individuated.

116
00:11:10,109 --> 00:11:12,071
And it takes, it seems, three years.

117
00:11:12,910 --> 00:11:19,357
The first four months, it seems to be just a blanket of sensations which has no depth.

118
00:11:19,378 --> 00:11:26,965
So when we see little babies reaching out and actually creating their 3D world, and very slowly, over a period of time,

119
00:11:27,129 --> 00:11:33,118
this mass of sensations becomes the world out there and me.

120
00:11:34,058 --> 00:11:39,145
That's why by about the age of three, children could say, I am a boy, I am a girl.

121
00:11:39,166 --> 00:11:41,248
They're very clear about their little existences.

122
00:11:44,152 --> 00:11:48,378
All we are doing is externalizing the inner world.

123
00:11:48,398 --> 00:11:52,462
All we are doing is, as it were, pushing away the inner world

124
00:11:52,797 --> 00:11:58,304
so that it becomes an inner world that seems outer.

125
00:11:58,325 --> 00:12:03,231
I'm sure I'm making myself perfectly clear.

126
00:12:03,251 --> 00:12:21,116
So, when you find this position within yourself, it was very, it's been named the observation post by Jnana Poniketera in what is still, you know, the classic book on meditation, The Heart of Buddhist Meditation.

127
00:12:22,649 --> 00:12:29,599
We access within us an observation post and we feel ourselves to be the observer of thoughts and feelings.

128
00:12:30,200 --> 00:12:33,083
We experience ourselves to be the feeler.

129
00:12:33,303 --> 00:12:37,330
We can feel pain in the knee and so on.

130
00:12:37,350 --> 00:12:38,510
We feel the breath.

131
00:12:38,530 --> 00:12:40,293
We can experience it directly.

132
00:12:40,833 --> 00:12:44,119
And yet, our identity is of the observer.

133
00:12:46,522 --> 00:12:51,929
In the moments of real clarity within your meditation, when you are

134
00:12:52,331 --> 00:13:08,033
and the body is perfectly still, and the heart is perfectly calm, and the mind has stopped even for a second, and you really feel yourself, you really experience yourself to be the observer within this psychophysical organism.

135
00:13:08,735 --> 00:13:14,743
When you've done that, ask yourself afterwards, what were the inner contents of the observer?

136
00:13:14,923 --> 00:13:18,668
What's it made of?

137
00:13:18,688 --> 00:13:20,971
Did you find any sensations in there?

138
00:13:21,475 --> 00:13:24,940
Did we find any bodily parts in there?

139
00:13:24,960 --> 00:13:27,583
Were there any feelings, emotions, moods?

140
00:13:29,005 --> 00:13:32,269
Were there any thoughts or images?

141
00:13:32,289 --> 00:13:38,899
And yet there was this bright, intuitive awareness.

142
00:13:38,919 --> 00:13:44,427
So what we've done there, unwittingly, is we've found where Nibbana is.

143
00:13:45,249 --> 00:13:47,432
It's staring us in the face, but we don't see it.

144
00:13:48,981 --> 00:13:57,972
Now the sense of self that we get, the sense of the observer, is the image of that very satipanya in the screen of consciousness.

145
00:13:59,674 --> 00:14:18,616
When we talk about consciousness, when we talk about the candor, the heap, the fifth part of what we call the five aggregates, which are the body and its feelings, all our perceptions, sorry, all our feelings, physical feelings, emotions as feelings,

146
00:14:19,086 --> 00:14:26,918
All our perceptions, which congregate to become our memories and help our thought patterns.

147
00:14:26,937 --> 00:14:30,422
All our conditionings, our sankhara, which is all our habits.

148
00:14:30,783 --> 00:14:34,347
And finally, this word, vijnana.

149
00:14:34,368 --> 00:14:39,894
It's translated as consciousness, but we don't really have a word for it in English, really.

150
00:14:40,596 --> 00:14:47,304
I tried to use the word cognition, but when I looked it up on the all-knowing Wikipedia, it didn't seem to fit either.

151
00:14:48,466 --> 00:14:49,547
It's a screen.

152
00:14:49,687 --> 00:14:55,572
Can you imagine all the information coming in onto your monitor or your TV screen?

153
00:14:55,592 --> 00:14:57,274
And somehow it's got to be held.

154
00:14:57,956 --> 00:15:01,499
It's got to be manifest.

155
00:15:01,519 --> 00:15:04,942
That manifestation is the manifestation of consciousness.

156
00:15:05,783 --> 00:15:09,047
And, peculiarly enough, it has its own intelligence.

157
00:15:09,586 --> 00:15:12,350
Just as the body has its own intelligence.

158
00:15:12,370 --> 00:15:14,572
When you cut yourself, do you get in there?

159
00:15:14,753 --> 00:15:16,293
Do you shift the cells around?

160
00:15:16,354 --> 00:15:17,054
What do you do?

161
00:15:17,288 --> 00:15:17,948
You do nothing.

162
00:15:18,028 --> 00:15:20,230
You keep it antiseptic.

163
00:15:20,250 --> 00:15:22,091
And the body does the rest.

164
00:15:22,131 --> 00:15:25,735
The body itself, the cellular life, has its own intelligence.

165
00:15:25,754 --> 00:15:27,677
So it is with our minds and hearts.

166
00:15:27,697 --> 00:15:34,062
We've developed a particular person, inverted commas, which works by itself.

167
00:15:34,442 --> 00:15:46,332
That's why you can be driving to work and thinking about all the problems of your life and arrive completely unharmed, having driven all that way, and you wonder where the two hours went.

168
00:15:47,596 --> 00:15:56,528
So there's something about the mind which has its own intelligence, but it needs to be put on the screen.

169
00:15:56,548 --> 00:16:08,945
Our delusion is to fall into the screen, on the monitor, on the TV, and become whatever is happening at that time.

170
00:16:10,466 --> 00:16:15,813
When we come into meditation, we're pulling ourselves out of that mass, and we're making it an object.

171
00:16:16,029 --> 00:16:17,631
We're making it something to observe.

172
00:16:17,851 --> 00:16:24,240
And in so doing, as soon as we observe it, it obviously can't be me.

173
00:16:24,259 --> 00:16:33,071
However, when we get there, and sometimes when you're watching television, you will see your image in the screen, and you have a choice.

174
00:16:33,091 --> 00:16:36,936
Are you going to watch TV, or are you going to watch yourself watching TV?

175
00:16:38,097 --> 00:16:43,083
So the sense of the observer is the image of this satipanya,

176
00:16:43,519 --> 00:16:50,471
this intuitive awareness in the screen of cognition, in the screen of consciousness, for want of a better word.

177
00:16:52,634 --> 00:16:55,638
Unfortunately, you can't get rid of it by an act of will.

178
00:16:56,419 --> 00:17:02,008
And you can only get rid of it by paying attention to the object that's before you.

179
00:17:02,028 --> 00:17:07,395
When you pay attention to the object that's before you, you're going to absorb into it.

180
00:17:08,837 --> 00:17:10,000
Depending on

181
00:17:10,604 --> 00:17:18,113
the intention with which you enter that absorption, you come out the other end having developed that intention.

182
00:17:18,133 --> 00:17:33,152
If you saw something which you particularly liked, ice cream on a hot day, and you just went for it, and thoroughly indulged in it with two corners, you would come out of that experience with even more desire for ice cream.

183
00:17:34,292 --> 00:17:36,695
However, if you went into that experience

184
00:17:37,097 --> 00:17:50,796
without the greed, but just to enjoy, very difficult to separate, then you come out of it with a greater sense of enjoyment without the attachment.

185
00:17:50,816 --> 00:18:00,409
We find we wouldn't get attached so much to things if we began to recognize the aftermath.

186
00:18:00,429 --> 00:18:06,717
The aftermath of attachment, the aftermath of indulgence is the frustration of not being able to get what you want.

187
00:18:07,844 --> 00:18:09,806
It's the grief of losing what you have.

188
00:18:10,686 --> 00:18:15,673
It's the constant fear of loss anyway, so you take out an insurance policy.

189
00:18:15,692 --> 00:18:20,659
There's a sense of compulsive behavior behind it, and worst of all, boredom.

190
00:18:21,740 --> 00:18:28,888
Because of the inbuilt obsolescence of pleasure, we can't keep chewing the same sweet.

191
00:18:29,348 --> 00:18:31,250
We've got to have a different flavor.

192
00:18:32,353 --> 00:18:37,057
And so we get caught up in this search for happiness in the central world,

193
00:18:37,627 --> 00:18:48,284
The search for happiness in relationship, the search for happiness in art, in nature, wherever we think we can find happiness, the search goes on.

194
00:18:49,326 --> 00:19:05,069
However, if we begin to enter into these experiences with the right intention, then we don't get that stickiness, and we find that we can enjoy life without these unfortunate consequences.

195
00:19:07,345 --> 00:19:15,876
Conversely, if we enter into a situation of aversion, then of course we end up with conflict.

196
00:19:15,896 --> 00:19:17,699
And that has its own problems.

197
00:19:19,622 --> 00:19:20,462
Pretty straightforward.

198
00:19:20,983 --> 00:19:36,525
So our aim in daily life is to take the aversion, to take the suffering out of pain, all sorts of pain, physical, emotional, relationship, whatever, take the suffering out of it, and to take the indulgence out of pleasure.

199
00:19:36,893 --> 00:19:41,198
That's our practice, in one way of looking at it, in ordinary daily life.

200
00:19:42,318 --> 00:19:53,230
In the inner life, in our meditation and in our contemplations, our process is always to make things something to observe, something to investigate.

201
00:19:54,030 --> 00:20:01,578
And that process makes more and more obvious to us this quality within us which is happily called the knowing.

202
00:20:02,299 --> 00:20:04,082
So Ajahn Tate, who

203
00:20:04,450 --> 00:20:17,704
who was a very famous monk in Thailand, lived up on the Mekong River, was considered to be an Arahant, and when he died, two million people turned up to his funeral, so presumably he earned his reputation.

204
00:20:17,724 --> 00:20:24,953
And he had this lovely little phrase of saying, make it simple, take it easy, stay with the one who knows.

205
00:20:25,694 --> 00:20:32,001
And that was probably his guiding line, which brought him his own insights.

206
00:20:32,041 --> 00:20:32,162
So,

207
00:20:32,664 --> 00:20:40,994
This process of re-identifying ourselves backward into the observer is the process of relief.

208
00:20:41,055 --> 00:20:43,958
It's the process of unshackling ourselves.

209
00:20:44,739 --> 00:20:50,645
So nirvana turns out to be the unshackling of this intuitive awareness.

210
00:20:51,247 --> 00:20:52,888
That's the process that we're going through.

211
00:20:56,713 --> 00:21:00,478
And we can only hope that when we get there, that's it.

212
00:21:01,048 --> 00:21:02,431
and there isn't anything else.

213
00:21:05,473 --> 00:21:08,116
I can only hope my words have been of some assistance.

214
00:21:08,518 --> 00:21:16,948
May you, by your fierce practice, enter into that wonderful state of the end of suffering sooner rather than later.

215
00:21:21,192 --> 00:21:23,035
What happens now then?

216
00:21:29,021 --> 00:21:30,042
I hope you come again.

217
00:21:30,461 --> 00:21:33,645
And let's have a cup of tea.

218
00:21:33,665 --> 00:21:35,608
What about that?

219
00:21:35,848 --> 00:21:36,971
Is that a good thing?

220
00:21:37,571 --> 00:21:41,317
Questions and answers?

221
00:21:41,797 --> 00:21:42,357
Questions?

222
00:21:42,377 --> 00:21:46,002
Yeah, that's a question.

223
00:21:47,444 --> 00:21:50,788
I don't have one.

224
00:21:50,990 --> 00:21:58,680
I didn't quite catch what you said about what happened to the Buddha when he ate a rice cake.

225
00:21:58,913 --> 00:22:07,080
Well, what I'm suggesting is that sometime around that point, he remembers this occasion in childhood.

226
00:22:07,862 --> 00:22:14,488
So there must have been some connection with, you know, like Proust, the Madeleine.

227
00:22:14,508 --> 00:22:16,289
I mean, it all comes back to him, you know.

228
00:22:16,750 --> 00:22:22,454
So he remembers his father, and he just recalls that state.

229
00:22:22,796 --> 00:22:27,299
Now, if you think about children, you'll notice how they...

230
00:22:27,617 --> 00:22:31,942
suddenly lock onto something, a bug they haven't seen or something.

231
00:22:31,962 --> 00:22:35,728
And when they do that, their eyes just lock and the world disappears.

232
00:22:37,089 --> 00:22:38,070
And their jaw drops.

233
00:22:38,530 --> 00:22:43,176
And to us, more developed beings, we think they look gormless.

234
00:22:43,958 --> 00:22:47,382
We give them a crack on the back of the head and they wake up.

235
00:22:47,402 --> 00:22:51,106
Thereby destroying their ability to become fully liberated.

236
00:22:52,167 --> 00:22:52,949
This is what happens.

237
00:22:54,351 --> 00:22:56,173
When the child is locked in like that,

238
00:22:57,502 --> 00:22:58,324
there's no thought.

239
00:22:59,505 --> 00:23:03,449
Their attention is completely absorbed in receiving the information.

240
00:23:04,869 --> 00:23:10,815
When the jaw drops it tells us that there's no thought, because the jaw, the tongue are intimately connected to thinking.

241
00:23:11,736 --> 00:23:15,400
So at that point they are in a state of pure observation.

242
00:23:17,741 --> 00:23:19,143
That's what we need to get back to.

243
00:23:20,403 --> 00:23:21,404
That's original mind.

244
00:23:22,105 --> 00:23:26,430
So Buddha had that memory of his father.

245
00:23:27,440 --> 00:23:32,807
And having that memory of his father led him to...

246
00:23:32,827 --> 00:23:35,371
Right, he turned around upon his meditation.

247
00:23:36,071 --> 00:23:37,835
He turned around on his meditation?

248
00:23:37,914 --> 00:23:39,698
Right, I'm putting it that way.

249
00:23:42,361 --> 00:23:45,967
Before, he'd been practicing in order to be happy.

250
00:23:47,087 --> 00:23:54,679
So the first practices were these absorption states, which are, in all religions, which are

251
00:23:54,997 --> 00:24:00,242
Something that you've created within yourself through mantra, through the fact of metta that we do.

252
00:24:00,262 --> 00:24:04,748
The beauty of those is that you don't need anything outside you.

253
00:24:04,768 --> 00:24:14,259
So therefore, all you need is a couple of rites, a tree, a bowl to go around and get a bit of food, and you can sit there all day completely blissed out.

254
00:24:14,278 --> 00:24:22,387
But unfortunately you kept waking up, out of that state, and finding that actually you're still depressed, anxious,

255
00:24:23,211 --> 00:24:25,193
So it was a false state that happened.

256
00:24:25,394 --> 00:24:27,134
And he left those teachers because of that.

257
00:24:28,195 --> 00:24:35,221
The other side was self-mortification, which is the idea that if you could release, if you could get rid of the...

258
00:24:35,563 --> 00:24:36,743
The problem was the body.

259
00:24:38,005 --> 00:24:41,248
So you got rid of all sex, drugs, rock and roll.

260
00:24:42,127 --> 00:24:46,332
You began not to eat, to draw the body down to its essentials.

261
00:24:47,432 --> 00:24:52,257
And as I've said, the James Saint actually takes it to the point of death after release.

262
00:24:52,574 --> 00:24:55,237
and for them, for the Jain religion, they are heroes.

263
00:24:56,817 --> 00:25:00,682
He tried that, but he just found it to be more suffering.

264
00:25:00,701 --> 00:25:20,421
So, he then, you know, has this experience, as far as I'm concerned, he's in a state of despair, because he's received all the teachings that were there, and he's still in a state of complete confusion and quandary, and presumably thinking that, well, this is it, you know, it's just going to be birth after birth,

265
00:25:21,109 --> 00:25:50,289
you know one lifetime a cow and a pig which sounds pretty miserable so he he's sitting there and then somebody comes along gives him this bit of ice you know this sweetmeat and he he has this memory and somehow it changes his view of what he's trying to seek of what he's what he's searching for so instead of trying to seek happiness he says well why am I why am I suffering what's the cause of this suffering

266
00:25:50,894 --> 00:25:58,865
And it's that which makes him sit under the tree with this new inspiration of turning inward and observing how he's creating suffering.

267
00:25:59,586 --> 00:26:04,134
And this later comes out in the teaching of dependent origination, which is a psychology.

268
00:26:05,255 --> 00:26:10,042
And the teaching of dependent origination clearly delineates where the problem lies.

269
00:26:10,063 --> 00:26:11,263
It does not lie in the body.

270
00:26:11,284 --> 00:26:13,247
It does not lie in our sense bases.

271
00:26:13,688 --> 00:26:16,893
It does not lie in the feelings and emotions that come up.

272
00:26:16,913 --> 00:26:19,737
It lies in our relationship to what we're experiencing.

273
00:26:20,289 --> 00:26:21,250
That's the core of it.

274
00:26:21,631 --> 00:26:23,794
And that relationship is desire.

275
00:26:24,013 --> 00:26:24,835
Wrong desire.

276
00:26:26,436 --> 00:26:31,461
But even at the point of desire, in the meditation, you'll know that there's no suffering.

277
00:26:31,962 --> 00:26:37,269
Because desire, as it comes up as an intention, is still not manifest.

278
00:26:37,288 --> 00:26:40,551
It just remains as a force within the mind.

279
00:26:41,373 --> 00:26:45,978
It's only when you fall into the identity of it that the suffering begins.

280
00:26:47,380 --> 00:26:49,622
So the process is the seeing,

281
00:26:50,615 --> 00:27:06,789
the initial experience, the way that we divide the world into what's pleasant and unpleasant, and then the desire for the pleasant, and then I want the desire for the pleasant.

282
00:27:06,809 --> 00:27:15,336
So although in English we say I want, I see, want, I scream, it's the other way around.

283
00:27:16,157 --> 00:27:18,359
I scream, see, want, I.

284
00:27:18,896 --> 00:27:21,039
If it weren't that way around, there'd be no escape.

285
00:27:24,184 --> 00:27:29,453
If the whole process began with I, you wouldn't be able to get out of it, because it's always you.

286
00:27:30,515 --> 00:27:41,692
It's the fact that the process is before the I arises, is not you, is not identifiable, and you can step out of that process and observe it, and it's passing.

287
00:27:42,334 --> 00:27:46,119
And in so doing, you're actually seeing the escape route from suffering.

288
00:27:49,423 --> 00:27:56,652
If you haven't understood this in the words, then you must come up to Satipaññā and do a retreat.

289
00:27:59,335 --> 00:28:02,679
So really then what you're saying is our real eye is our spiritual nature?

290
00:28:02,719 --> 00:28:05,882
Yeah.

291
00:28:06,403 --> 00:28:07,523
Why not?

292
00:28:07,544 --> 00:28:11,588
You're also saying not to take it personally, in a sense, aren't you?

293
00:28:11,608 --> 00:28:13,490
Because it's not about the eye.

294
00:28:14,769 --> 00:28:18,615
Well, you have to be careful with this one, because the Buddha never said there was no self.

295
00:28:18,875 --> 00:28:19,777
He just said it was false.

296
00:28:21,078 --> 00:28:26,247
And it's recognizing the false nature of the self, which is the process of disidentifying.

297
00:28:27,548 --> 00:28:31,413
So whenever I say, I am depressed, where's the escape?

298
00:28:31,433 --> 00:28:37,702
As soon as I say, oh, there's depression, I've escaped.

299
00:28:37,722 --> 00:28:41,588
I've come out of that process of identity.

300
00:28:41,608 --> 00:28:41,689
See?

301
00:28:44,233 --> 00:28:48,137
Except the depression remains.

302
00:28:48,917 --> 00:28:55,203
I know it's a drag.

303
00:28:55,284 --> 00:28:56,585
Everything changes.

304
00:28:56,605 --> 00:28:59,548
Remember that the heart will heal itself.

305
00:29:00,088 --> 00:29:01,369
You don't have to do anything.

306
00:29:01,650 --> 00:29:03,592
This is the magic of the whole system.

307
00:29:04,952 --> 00:29:06,954
All there is, is energy.

308
00:29:07,776 --> 00:29:12,299
It's the mind which describes it as depression and puts a history to it and a future to it.

309
00:29:12,667 --> 00:29:15,751
When you stay with the depression, there's no depression, there's just weight.

310
00:29:16,593 --> 00:29:19,195
See, in the East, they somatize their problems.

311
00:29:19,336 --> 00:29:21,598
Here, we always psychologize it.

312
00:29:21,618 --> 00:29:24,102
You get a pain in the knee and it's deep anxiety.

313
00:29:24,923 --> 00:29:27,747
Whereas in the East, they just say it's a pain in the knee.

314
00:29:27,767 --> 00:29:30,250
So if they're depressed, they're not depressed, they just feel heavy.

315
00:29:31,751 --> 00:29:32,332
See?

316
00:29:32,352 --> 00:29:33,753
And there's a little escape from that.

317
00:29:33,773 --> 00:29:35,836
At least you don't identify so much with it.

318
00:29:37,778 --> 00:29:40,903
And what we discover in our meditation is just by

319
00:29:41,086 --> 00:29:45,951
Allowing it to express itself is the process of healing.

320
00:29:46,633 --> 00:29:47,673
It's as simple as that.

321
00:29:49,636 --> 00:29:51,959
And much cheaper.

322
00:29:51,979 --> 00:30:10,182
And remember that we're not moving towards some sort of dead heart state, you know, like the Buddha sitting under the tree, blank,

323
00:30:10,701 --> 00:30:14,145
with a sign, fully liberated, do not be stirred.

324
00:30:15,327 --> 00:30:17,210
I mean, he ends up with the Buddha heart.

325
00:30:18,090 --> 00:30:33,351
So all these emotional states that we have, depression, loneliness, anxiety, when they come up, that energy is not dissipated, it transforms, it sublimates.

326
00:30:34,089 --> 00:30:40,739
As I understand sublimation in science, it is a solid which moves directly into a gas without an in-between.

327
00:30:41,440 --> 00:30:53,636
So, although we have ice, water and vapour, it seems though if you have something which goes from solid to vapour immediately, they call that sublimation.

328
00:30:53,656 --> 00:30:55,920
That's exactly what's happening all the time.

329
00:30:55,940 --> 00:30:57,803
As soon as you sit with your depression,

330
00:30:58,238 --> 00:31:12,136
or your anxiety, and you're feeling it, and you're staying with it, and you're holding it and embracing it in loving kindness, affectionate awareness, as you see, it feels as though it's evaporating, right?

331
00:31:12,156 --> 00:31:13,818
After a time, of course.

332
00:31:13,838 --> 00:31:17,443
And that is changing into its opposite immediately.

333
00:31:18,424 --> 00:31:23,352
And you know that because the next time you behave, there's a change of behavior, even if only small.

334
00:31:23,855 --> 00:31:32,124
So where there was hatred, you find love, where there's cruelty, compassion, selfishness, generosity, loneliness, solitude.

335
00:31:41,795 --> 00:31:43,236
Happy days are ahead of us.

336
00:31:48,682 --> 00:31:53,186
So a lot of this is about using language to make

337
00:31:53,385 --> 00:32:00,675
the state objective out there and constantly returning to that practice, would you say?

338
00:32:00,715 --> 00:32:15,096
It's in the technique that I personally teach, which is taught by the Maharshi side of Burma, we do use a noting technique to make that distance obvious.

339
00:32:15,115 --> 00:32:16,837
But that is only a technique.

340
00:32:17,239 --> 00:32:21,064
It's not so much to do with language as an inner position that you take.

341
00:32:25,886 --> 00:32:28,409
See, I mentioned catching your finger in the door.

342
00:32:28,548 --> 00:32:31,832
See, for one moment, you and the finger are one.

343
00:32:31,852 --> 00:32:34,034
You become a physical self.

344
00:32:35,115 --> 00:32:39,098
And then you jump out of that and you become the angry self and start kicking the door.

345
00:32:42,842 --> 00:32:44,683
So this sense of self is always moving.

346
00:32:45,345 --> 00:32:46,425
It's always changing.

347
00:32:46,445 --> 00:32:48,688
It's always catching the hold of something.

348
00:32:49,127 --> 00:32:53,311
What is it that is falling into this identity?

349
00:32:55,621 --> 00:32:55,961
Buddha.

350
00:32:58,484 --> 00:33:01,409
It's the satipanyas, the awareness.

351
00:33:01,589 --> 00:33:04,473
It's the Buddha within that suffering.

352
00:33:04,493 --> 00:33:05,674
The body doesn't suffer.

353
00:33:05,694 --> 00:33:06,375
It just has pain.

354
00:33:07,017 --> 00:33:07,939
The heart doesn't suffer.

355
00:33:07,959 --> 00:33:09,099
It just has emotions.

356
00:33:09,119 --> 00:33:09,901
The mind doesn't suffer.

357
00:33:09,921 --> 00:33:10,362
It just works.

358
00:33:11,002 --> 00:33:12,565
What's suffering is the Buddha within.

359
00:33:12,925 --> 00:33:14,627
That's why we're trying to get out of it.

360
00:33:16,830 --> 00:33:19,615
You're all looking at me very serious.

361
00:33:19,634 --> 00:33:21,577
You're beginning to feel I'm saying heretical things.

362
00:33:25,996 --> 00:33:28,298
Can I ask, do you mean by the Buddha within?

363
00:33:28,318 --> 00:33:32,482
Is that an awareness of the fact that we can get out of it?

364
00:33:32,803 --> 00:33:33,763
Is that the Buddha within?

365
00:33:35,226 --> 00:33:38,910
The Buddha within refers to the quality of intuitive awareness.

366
00:33:41,192 --> 00:33:43,013
These are not two sides of the same coin.

367
00:33:43,214 --> 00:33:45,057
These are not two different faculties.

368
00:33:45,076 --> 00:33:46,778
They're two sides of the same coin.

369
00:33:47,159 --> 00:33:48,721
First you look and then you see.

370
00:33:48,760 --> 00:33:54,686
But for it to be active, there has to be a desire to know.

371
00:33:56,641 --> 00:34:10,179
Could you take us through a little process of, for example, I've been just now, based on what you've been saying, working with a certain issue to try and release the Buddha within.

372
00:34:10,980 --> 00:34:14,264
So there is grief.

373
00:34:14,385 --> 00:34:16,467
I'm grieving, so there is grief.

374
00:34:16,487 --> 00:34:21,594
And then I feel disloyal in a way because I'm not grieving anymore.

375
00:34:22,315 --> 00:34:24,858
So then I say there is disloyalty.

376
00:34:25,074 --> 00:34:32,543
and I'm sort of free of that, and then somehow I'm...

377
00:34:32,563 --> 00:34:33,284
Stuck.

378
00:34:33,304 --> 00:34:36,327
Yeah, I'm not sure where I am.

379
00:34:36,628 --> 00:34:37,268
Right, okay.

380
00:34:37,289 --> 00:34:42,235
Well, first of all, in this particular case, our confusion is between sorrow and grief.

381
00:34:43,135 --> 00:34:47,380
Sorrow is the resonance within our own hearts of somebody else's suffering.

382
00:34:47,400 --> 00:34:49,043
Grief is the measure of our attachment.

383
00:34:50,083 --> 00:34:52,786
So when somebody dies or somebody leaves us,

384
00:34:53,088 --> 00:34:57,014
It's like something just ripped out of our hearts and we're just left with this sore.

385
00:34:59,177 --> 00:35:03,682
And then if we think that that is a measure of our love, then how can we stop grieving?

386
00:35:03,824 --> 00:35:06,306
Because every time we stop grieving, we think we've stopped loving.

387
00:35:08,010 --> 00:35:12,076
We get into a double bind.

388
00:35:12,096 --> 00:35:19,746
So once we realize that the grief I'm feeling is something personal to me because of the relationship I had and there's nothing to do with love.

389
00:35:20,427 --> 00:35:21,929
Love is very easy.

390
00:35:22,112 --> 00:35:23,614
Love lets people die.

391
00:35:24,135 --> 00:35:24,817
It's not a problem.

392
00:35:25,177 --> 00:35:26,500
Love lets people leave us.

393
00:35:28,103 --> 00:35:29,043
But grief doesn't.

394
00:35:29,244 --> 00:35:30,085
Grief hangs on.

395
00:35:30,646 --> 00:35:49,757
And so we sit with the grief, not confusing it with love, love denied, but seeing it as the product of attachment, which means, attachment means we are psychologically dependent on something outside our control for our happiness.

396
00:35:51,003 --> 00:35:54,849
Once you begin to realize that, it's a no-goer.

397
00:35:54,869 --> 00:36:00,317
You just don't invest in bonds that aren't going to work.

398
00:36:02,239 --> 00:36:07,086
So, you observe the grief, and the grief, and the heart will heal itself.

399
00:36:07,947 --> 00:36:11,592
It may take a week, a month, nine months, it doesn't matter.

400
00:36:11,632 --> 00:36:14,077
The heart will just slowly heal itself.

401
00:36:14,097 --> 00:36:19,525
I had a particularly interesting case of that, of an elderly woman who came

402
00:36:19,757 --> 00:36:23,322
saying that she'd been grieving for her son for five years.

403
00:36:24,903 --> 00:36:27,085
And this was exactly what she was doing.

404
00:36:27,567 --> 00:36:32,811
She was grieving, and every time the grief went, she felt guilty that she no longer loved her son.

405
00:36:33,452 --> 00:36:38,097
As soon as this was pointed out to her, she was back the next week saying all the grief had gone.

406
00:36:42,463 --> 00:36:43,503
There is an end to grief.

407
00:36:45,965 --> 00:36:50,309
You do get like an emotional, it has an emotional sort of scar as well, doesn't it?

408
00:36:50,990 --> 00:36:56,277
You can see a photo, the grief can come back, or you can just remember something, the grief comes back.

409
00:36:56,297 --> 00:36:56,516
Yeah.

410
00:36:57,978 --> 00:37:02,324
Yeah, but hopefully, eventually, there's just the memory of joys.

411
00:37:03,646 --> 00:37:11,414
I mean, you counterbalance that with gratefulness, gratitude, that, you know, you had a lovely relationship.

412
00:37:11,434 --> 00:37:14,318
Even if it was a terrible relationship, you're grateful for the teachings.

413
00:37:17,757 --> 00:37:23,623
Yes, that's it.

414
00:37:23,643 --> 00:37:25,144
It's called Tough Love.

415
00:37:25,626 --> 00:37:47,409
I was quite interested in what you were saying about the difference in the way that we look at emotional, psychological, we call them psychological problems in the West, of depression, anxiety, trauma, whatever, and that it's experienced more as a somatic

416
00:37:47,777 --> 00:38:01,170
sensation is, do you think there is working with feelings in the body rather than the cognitions is actually quite helpful when you're meditating?

417
00:38:04,173 --> 00:38:10,981
When something happens to us, say, just a very simple thing, somebody says something that irritates us.

418
00:38:12,302 --> 00:38:17,768
So all that's happening is that we can see their face and

419
00:38:18,338 --> 00:38:19,739
their attitude towards us.

420
00:38:20,019 --> 00:38:26,869
We hear the coarse words or the words that they want to be painful to us.

421
00:38:26,889 --> 00:38:29,952
That's all.

422
00:38:29,972 --> 00:38:34,478
We might feel at the heart level, at this sort of surface heart level, the vibration of their anger.

423
00:38:34,699 --> 00:38:35,159
That's all.

424
00:38:35,661 --> 00:38:38,103
The rest is completely manufactured by me.

425
00:38:38,864 --> 00:38:45,012
So if I now allow anger to arise against that, that's been manufactured by me.

426
00:38:46,335 --> 00:38:46,675
So,

427
00:38:47,211 --> 00:38:57,204
All these emotions that we feel, the depression, the anxiety, etc., etc., have not been directly caused by someone else or an event.

428
00:38:58,425 --> 00:39:07,356
There is nothing in the world, or anybody in the world, who can actually cause me psychological suffering.

429
00:39:07,376 --> 00:39:17,067
If it were true that other people could cause me psychological suffering, how could I have ever been liberated, say, by getting rid of you?

430
00:39:21,146 --> 00:39:26,914
It's the very fact that all the suffering I have is caused by me, that the liberation is possible here and now.

431
00:39:29,717 --> 00:39:29,797
See?

432
00:39:29,817 --> 00:39:39,228
So now, if all this anger in me, just saying anger in me, is not caused, I'm still left with the conditioning of anger.

433
00:39:39,248 --> 00:39:41,552
It remains in me like a red hot balloon.

434
00:39:42,413 --> 00:39:43,634
And it seeks objects.

435
00:39:43,974 --> 00:39:45,215
I can get angry with anything.

436
00:39:46,617 --> 00:39:49,280
It just depends whether this is coming to the surface or not.

437
00:39:50,105 --> 00:39:53,608
And that's why a lot of our anger is inappropriate.

438
00:39:55,710 --> 00:40:01,576
When you go home and your partner or husband has not done something, you can really burst out in a huge amount of anger.

439
00:40:02,436 --> 00:40:04,219
But if it's your boss, you've got to swallow it.

440
00:40:04,358 --> 00:40:07,702
You've got to keep it down.

441
00:40:09,344 --> 00:40:15,829
When you consider that there is this ball of anger, which has nothing to do with past, present and future.

442
00:40:15,889 --> 00:40:17,952
It is a present conditioning within us.

443
00:40:18,809 --> 00:40:21,612
which has, of course, its own inner conditioning of triggers.

444
00:40:21,652 --> 00:40:23,735
Certain things make us more angry than others.

445
00:40:24,916 --> 00:40:31,903
Our problem is to release the anger as feeling, because all it is, is energy.

446
00:40:33,485 --> 00:40:44,038
And it's in sitting within the bonfire, with, of course, affection and kindness, that the process of healing happens.

447
00:40:44,057 --> 00:40:47,061
You don't have to do anything in the outside world.

448
00:40:48,981 --> 00:41:18,567
If in your meditation you're working with some sort of emotional pain, and you're sat there, and suddenly a memory comes up, which seems to be the point where this whole mental conditioning arose, it can be a vehicle through which there's an escape for that particular suffering, and it can be a healing moment, right?

449
00:41:19,086 --> 00:41:22,891
So a traumatic moment.

450
00:41:22,911 --> 00:41:25,353
But you can't make that come.

451
00:41:25,373 --> 00:41:29,297
That has to come out of the psyche, out of the mind.

452
00:41:31,858 --> 00:41:44,192
Sometimes you get pain in the body, which you know is emotionally based, it's not physical, and you sit with it, and sit with it, and sit with it, and it disappears, and you haven't a clue what it was.

453
00:41:44,411 --> 00:41:46,713
You might intuitively think that it was

454
00:41:46,963 --> 00:41:48,364
anxiety, but you don't know.

455
00:41:48,405 --> 00:41:51,728
All you know is that there was discomfort and pain in the body.

456
00:41:53,911 --> 00:41:59,016
But then when it's gone, you know that something's left and you feel the lighter and better for it.

457
00:41:59,996 --> 00:42:06,222
And it's when you have those sorts of experiences that you realize that actually the heart heals itself.

458
00:42:06,583 --> 00:42:08,043
All you have to do is get out of the way.

459
00:42:10,126 --> 00:42:16,853
But it can't do it without expressing its disturbances within your awareness.

460
00:42:17,557 --> 00:42:26,789
Until it does so, it's stuck within the frame of this psychophysical organism, a phrase I particularly like.

461
00:42:26,809 --> 00:42:27,449
Does that make sense?

462
00:42:28,510 --> 00:42:29,072
Yeah.

463
00:42:32,135 --> 00:42:35,739
Could you tell us a little bit about yourself, how you've arrived to where you are?

464
00:42:37,121 --> 00:42:38,181
Where you started.

465
00:42:38,322 --> 00:42:39,344
Well, it's really boring.

466
00:42:41,766 --> 00:42:45,590
Boring to you.

467
00:42:46,567 --> 00:42:50,331
Yeah, it's just me.

468
00:42:50,411 --> 00:42:51,092
It's just me.

469
00:42:51,112 --> 00:42:52,373
It's just boring.

470
00:42:52,994 --> 00:42:54,617
Could you start with your name?

471
00:42:54,757 --> 00:42:55,677
Ah, my name.

472
00:42:55,818 --> 00:42:56,458
Bodhidharma.

473
00:42:56,539 --> 00:42:57,179
Bodhidharma.

474
00:42:57,199 --> 00:42:58,342
Yeah, well, that was given to me.

475
00:42:58,382 --> 00:43:00,704
That's given to you by your teacher, you see, when you ordain.

476
00:43:01,105 --> 00:43:06,472
And he knew I had a Zen background, so I think it's a bit tongue-in-cheek.

477
00:43:06,492 --> 00:43:08,393
In the...

478
00:43:08,695 --> 00:43:12,079
In the...

479
00:43:12,179 --> 00:43:15,222
In the ordination...

480
00:43:15,996 --> 00:43:20,623
In the way of naming monastics, it's taken on the day of your birth.

481
00:43:21,644 --> 00:43:28,673
And it follows, the days of the week follow the alphabet, the Sanskrit or Pali alphabet.

482
00:43:28,773 --> 00:43:35,003
So the first day would be the vowels, A, E, O, U, see?

483
00:43:35,023 --> 00:43:44,215
And then it would start at the back with G, K, V. Well, on Wednesday, which is on a Wednesday's child, it's M and V. So you didn't have much of a choice.

484
00:43:44,666 --> 00:43:46,489
So he ends up with Bodhidharma.

485
00:43:48,090 --> 00:43:53,996
And as you know, he's the great Indian who went to India and started the whole Chan tradition.

486
00:43:54,016 --> 00:43:56,237
And was, for some reason, named after me.

487
00:43:58,480 --> 00:44:03,105
So you just get your name like that.

488
00:44:03,125 --> 00:44:04,646
It's not that you can't change it.

489
00:44:05,166 --> 00:44:13,375
I have a rather interesting story of a Dutchman who was ordained and was given the name of one of the companions of the Buddha.

490
00:44:15,396 --> 00:44:19,161
The companion of the Buddha was called Whopper.

491
00:44:22,744 --> 00:44:26,228
When he finally copped a nod to what it meant, he was almost sniggering.

492
00:44:29,572 --> 00:44:30,373
Fancy Whopper.

493
00:44:33,737 --> 00:44:34,597
He changed his name.

494
00:44:35,978 --> 00:44:36,880
So it's not there.

495
00:44:36,900 --> 00:44:38,402
You're not stuck with that.

496
00:44:39,143 --> 00:44:41,184
Actually, the proper pronunciation should be Whop.

497
00:44:46,682 --> 00:45:09,804
doesn't fit the robe you know so yes no I as usual like a lot of people come into meditation because they're not they're not happy you know so I began I began way back there in a state of unhappiness seeking happiness and I I wrote I decided to go to Japan

498
00:45:10,206 --> 00:45:11,568
to do some meditation.

499
00:45:11,588 --> 00:45:19,239
So I wrote to the Buddhist Society in London and said, can you give me some idea or some direction on how to get to Japan to do some meditation?

500
00:45:19,260 --> 00:45:21,403
And they sent me a letter with 21 points.

501
00:45:21,463 --> 00:45:23,126
I wish I'd have kept it, as to why I shouldn't go.

502
00:45:26,210 --> 00:45:31,719
So then they said, there was a monastery just up in Northumberland, Trostle Hole Abbey.

503
00:45:32,380 --> 00:45:39,150
And they pointed to a teacher who was in Birmingham, Badgerow, and she lived but a little bus ride away.

504
00:45:40,057 --> 00:45:47,188
And I remember the first meditation, which was so Zen, you know, it was cool, the Zendo was very cool.

505
00:45:47,568 --> 00:45:50,413
And she had this sort of toughy look about her, you know.

506
00:45:50,432 --> 00:45:55,420
And she sat, she had me kneeling, you know, face the wall, you know, face the wall.

507
00:45:56,021 --> 00:46:03,050
And she said, her instructions were, watch whatever comes up.

508
00:46:03,070 --> 00:46:05,153
So I sat there and tried to watch whatever comes up.

509
00:46:05,193 --> 00:46:07,838
And all I can say is, at the end of 45 minutes...

510
00:46:07,987 --> 00:46:10,530
I just knew this was going to get me out of my problems.

511
00:46:11,932 --> 00:46:23,409
And by, within six months I had a job, I bought a house, and I was stealing clear of relationships after the former disastrous one.

512
00:46:23,809 --> 00:46:25,251
I was giving myself a break.

513
00:46:27,755 --> 00:46:34,585
And then about, by then the, I was living in Birmingham, with, and there was a,

514
00:46:35,492 --> 00:46:38,916
a Burmese monk there, some of you will know him, they were to Dhamma.

515
00:46:40,557 --> 00:46:42,820
And Vajra said, why don't we go and visit him?

516
00:46:42,880 --> 00:46:50,025
So I went over to visit him, and he's a PhD, and he was a PhD, he died in Abhidhamma.

517
00:46:50,045 --> 00:46:56,472
So I said to him, I thought I'd quiz him, and I said, Bhante, I said, what is your understanding of neurosis?

518
00:46:57,293 --> 00:46:59,474
And he looked at me and he said, what is that?

519
00:47:00,755 --> 00:47:03,458
And I thought, well, can I believe it?

520
00:47:03,876 --> 00:47:05,059
I'm lying about here.

521
00:47:05,259 --> 00:47:05,820
It's off away.

522
00:47:07,802 --> 00:47:14,333
Anyway, I was still drawn, and I had my first Theravada retreat with Ajahn Sumedho, Rumpur Sumedho.

523
00:47:15,916 --> 00:47:16,858
And it was very different.

524
00:47:17,958 --> 00:47:28,976
Although it's the same observation process, Zen kept me out of the five sense doors, and it was extremely good at daily life practice.

525
00:47:29,518 --> 00:47:30,880
And it really did change my life.

526
00:47:32,193 --> 00:47:35,717
I even took Dukkha up there, became a Buddhist there after two years.

527
00:47:35,737 --> 00:47:45,230
But in the retreat I did with Ajahn Sumedha, first one, closing my eyes and going inward was a massive revelation.

528
00:47:46,371 --> 00:47:50,516
I thought, this is it, I'm really actually investigating myself.

529
00:47:50,536 --> 00:47:53,460
And then shortly after that, the Mahasi Sayadaw came.

530
00:47:53,740 --> 00:47:54,842
I missed his first visit.

531
00:47:54,902 --> 00:47:58,706
On the second visit, I did a retreat with Sayadaw Janaka.

532
00:47:59,041 --> 00:48:05,313
And I just knew this guy was the beef.

533
00:48:06,193 --> 00:48:13,889
So I determined to go out and I took a sabbatical for work and spent six months with him in Burma.

534
00:48:14,148 --> 00:48:22,585
And then I came back and just this awful thing began to scratch on my mind, you know, sort of

535
00:48:23,425 --> 00:48:27,268
What I really needed, what I really wanted to do was dedicate myself to the practice.

536
00:48:27,349 --> 00:48:32,414
The only way you could do that was to become a monastic, because the institution is there for you to do that.

537
00:48:33,956 --> 00:48:42,186
And I resisted it, and then after about a year, I just went to Dr. Ududam and I said, Bandit said, I want to become a monk.

538
00:48:42,206 --> 00:48:43,266
And he said, you're too old.

539
00:48:45,550 --> 00:48:50,394
I thought, thank God for that.

540
00:48:50,661 --> 00:48:52,684
So I went off, but he just wouldn't let me go.

541
00:48:52,965 --> 00:48:56,088
So I came back again and I said, no, Bandi, I was about six months on.

542
00:48:57,110 --> 00:49:00,393
I said, no, no, Bandi, I think I really would like to ordain.

543
00:49:00,474 --> 00:49:04,518
And then he said, well, no, he said, you know, you're necessarily here.

544
00:49:04,557 --> 00:49:10,766
You know, because by then I was doing a little teaching and I was very much part of the fabric of the Bihara.

545
00:49:10,905 --> 00:49:13,489
You know, I mean, I cut the lawn for a start.

546
00:49:13,509 --> 00:49:16,112
And so...

547
00:49:16,581 --> 00:49:19,306
So again, I felt this sort of relief, oh yeah, right, okay.

548
00:49:19,365 --> 00:49:20,668
But unfortunately, he just wouldn't leave me.

549
00:49:20,688 --> 00:49:26,818
And I went on a two-week personal retreat in Wales, and I was really quite sure that's what I wanted to do.

550
00:49:26,838 --> 00:49:28,641
When I came back to him again, he said, okay.

551
00:49:30,123 --> 00:49:36,432
So I ordained in a very exotic place, which is Birmingham.

552
00:49:37,494 --> 00:49:39,458
And then from there, I went to Amrawati.

553
00:49:39,498 --> 00:49:41,019
I stayed there for about a year.

554
00:49:41,724 --> 00:49:45,829
I wanted to get myself to Burma, but all those terrible things happened in 89.

555
00:49:46,750 --> 00:49:52,574
And so quite, I was marooned really in Thailand, not knowing what to do, where to go.

556
00:49:53,356 --> 00:49:58,701
And I kept meeting monks who said, you know, you want to go to this Mahasi center in Sri Lanka.

557
00:49:58,740 --> 00:50:01,204
I've never even heard of it.

558
00:50:01,224 --> 00:50:05,086
And when I got there, there was this little hut and a nice little garden.

559
00:50:05,807 --> 00:50:07,610
And he gave it to me, the abbot.

560
00:50:07,949 --> 00:50:09,791
I sat there off and on for eight years.

561
00:50:10,867 --> 00:50:15,213
And then I came back because I felt, I didn't feel well.

562
00:50:15,454 --> 00:50:24,525
And I came back and had a contract, we can say, with the then head of the London Bodhisattva, Dr. Vajrayana.

563
00:50:25,407 --> 00:50:31,355
The idea was that I would stay there for the rainy season and just quietly meditate and whatever.

564
00:50:31,835 --> 00:50:33,378
And then I'd decide what to do.

565
00:50:34,179 --> 00:50:38,664
And during that time, the monk who was teaching meditation left and got married.

566
00:50:39,454 --> 00:50:47,885
So I got plonked onto the podium, and the teaching began, and I resisted it.

567
00:50:47,965 --> 00:50:50,188
I didn't even want to teach at all.

568
00:50:50,208 --> 00:50:57,275
And so it grew, and then in the year 2000, I went on a retreat with Sarupandita in his monastery.

569
00:50:58,237 --> 00:51:01,581
And it's funny, isn't it, how things happen?

570
00:51:02,021 --> 00:51:07,909
But it was really quite a koan, to put it in a Zen way, this teaching business.

571
00:51:08,057 --> 00:51:10,280
You know, there was something in me, I really didn't want to do it.

572
00:51:11,882 --> 00:51:14,103
And I was there for about two months.

573
00:51:14,664 --> 00:51:17,347
And at the end of the retreat, I just went into the library.

574
00:51:17,666 --> 00:51:19,849
And you know, the course of miracles.

575
00:51:20,530 --> 00:51:23,711
So here I am in Rangoon, in a Buddhist library.

576
00:51:24,452 --> 00:51:33,621
And there's a sliver of a book that catches my eye about teaching, which are all the quotes from the course of miracles as to why you should teach.

577
00:51:35,503 --> 00:51:37,304
So I read that and I knew I should teach.

578
00:51:37,521 --> 00:51:38,182
It's weird, isn't it?

579
00:51:38,342 --> 00:51:45,713
So I came back and established a little place in North London, which was an utter and complete catastrophe.

580
00:51:45,733 --> 00:51:46,554
I had to get out quick.

581
00:51:47,215 --> 00:51:56,847
And while I was up there, one of the people retreating with me was a man called Peter Meniam, who was very friendly with the bachelors.

582
00:51:57,329 --> 00:51:58,851
He knew Stephen well, it seems.

583
00:51:59,371 --> 00:52:03,376
So he knew my predicament now, because, you know, like, what am I going to do?

584
00:52:03,862 --> 00:52:06,146
I'd even contemplated leaving the Order.

585
00:52:06,646 --> 00:52:10,893
And so he wrote to Stephen and told him that the next Cosmic Buddha was in North London.

586
00:52:13,396 --> 00:52:27,576
It was just one of those lovely, fortunate positions where they'd left Gaia House and Yanai and Christina were holding the place with all these personal treasons and they needed somebody to help put it into that situation.

587
00:52:28,449 --> 00:52:31,313
And I stayed there, as some of you know, for four years.

588
00:52:31,393 --> 00:52:40,123
And during that time, it became obvious to me that there were enough people around who wanted to do the real McCoy.

589
00:52:40,644 --> 00:52:45,791
You know, the full-on get up at half past three, go to bed at ten, wallop.

590
00:52:46,773 --> 00:52:51,077
And I thought, well, there's a place there for a niche within a niche.

591
00:52:51,818 --> 00:52:56,684
So we began a little trust, and we've ended up on the borders of Wales.

592
00:52:57,188 --> 00:53:01,452
I only take eight people at a retreat, and only eight people come.

593
00:53:02,213 --> 00:53:06,237
And it's all right.

594
00:53:06,257 --> 00:53:08,420
It exists, and it continues.

595
00:53:08,440 --> 00:53:09,481
And you're all invited.

596
00:53:14,626 --> 00:53:16,369
And that's where I am at this present moment.

597
00:53:17,210 --> 00:53:19,532
And how long is the retreat?

598
00:53:19,552 --> 00:53:20,693
A minimum of a week.

599
00:53:20,713 --> 00:53:24,597
But during summer, I do a roll-on, roll-off, 11 weeks, a period, you see.

600
00:53:24,657 --> 00:53:25,878
People come from various lengths.

601
00:53:27,630 --> 00:53:30,394
And there are little retreats throughout the year too, week-long retreats.

602
00:53:30,675 --> 00:53:34,521
You really have to get up at half past three.

603
00:53:35,681 --> 00:53:37,123
Half past three is a wonderful time.

604
00:53:40,068 --> 00:53:41,150
Well, it's like anything else.

605
00:53:41,389 --> 00:53:51,083
After the first two days, when you get up a little later, five o'clock, you can feel the effects of the meditation.

606
00:53:51,103 --> 00:53:56,271
And so getting up at half past three is a bit of a struggle, but on day four, definitely by day five,

607
00:53:56,739 --> 00:53:58,282
One feels completely refreshed.

608
00:53:59,083 --> 00:53:59,764
Lots of energy.

609
00:54:01,967 --> 00:54:03,530
People cry by day seven.

610
00:54:03,550 --> 00:54:07,376
They just don't want to leave.

611
00:54:07,396 --> 00:54:08,898
But then that's only five hours sleep.

612
00:54:09,119 --> 00:54:09,498
How much?

613
00:54:10,039 --> 00:54:11,282
Five and a half hours.

614
00:54:11,302 --> 00:54:11,682
It's enough.

615
00:54:11,842 --> 00:54:14,226
Yes, five and a half hours.

616
00:54:14,246 --> 00:54:23,521
And then, of course, people who stay long term, even after about seven days, when they're used to that level of sleep, I push them back to four hours.

617
00:54:24,943 --> 00:54:25,684
And they're all there.

618
00:54:26,085 --> 00:54:31,293
Very few, only one or two have been able, have not been able to take that and come back to five and a half hours.

619
00:54:33,916 --> 00:54:36,420
We've got, you'd be surprised how much energy we have.

620
00:54:38,123 --> 00:54:41,967
And when you're running a retreat at Diane's, do they get up at half three?

621
00:54:42,208 --> 00:54:42,509
Yeah.

622
00:54:43,148 --> 00:54:43,469
Really?

623
00:54:43,489 --> 00:54:45,152
Yes, all week they've been up at half three.

624
00:54:45,192 --> 00:54:47,355
The first two days it's five o'clock and then they're up.

625
00:54:47,976 --> 00:54:48,617
Yes!

626
00:54:49,188 --> 00:55:18,047
25 people up there half past 3 till 10 o'clock yes mind you there were one or two laggards one has to be is that it thank you so much I shall ring the bell

627
00:55:19,528 --> 00:55:22,940
We won't play now.

